===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|lewbʰ}}
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|love}}, {{m|enm|luve}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lufu||love, affection, desire}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*lubō||love}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*lewbʰ-||love, care, desire}}. Cognate with {{etyl|ofs|-}} {{m|ofs|luve||love}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{m|goh|luba||love}}. Related to Old English {{m|ang|lēof||dear, beloved}}, Icelandic {{m|is|ljúf||dear, beloved}} and {{m|is|ljúfa||a dear person}}, {{m|ang|līefan||to allow, approve of}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{m|stq|Ljoowe||love}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{m|la|libet}}, {{m|la|lubō||to please}} and Albanian {{m|sq|lyp||to beg, ask insistently}}, {{m|sq|lips||to be demanded, needed}}, Serbo-Croatian {{m|sh|ljubiti}}, {{m|sh|ljubav}}, Russian {{m|ru|любо́вь}}, {{m|ru|люби́ть}}.

The closing-of-a-letter sense is presumably a truncation of ''With love'' or the like.

The verb is from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|loven}}, {{m|enm|lovien}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lufian||to love, cherish, sow love to; fondle, caress; delight in, approve, practice}}, from the noun {{m|ang|lufu||love}}. See above. Compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{m|fy|leavje||to love}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|lieben||to love}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{m|is|lofa||to prize}} and {{m|is|loforð||a promise}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{label|en|uncountable}} Strong affection.
## A profound and caring [[affection]] towards someone.
##: {{ux|en|A mother’s '''love''' is not easily shaken.}}
##: {{ux|en|My husband’s '''love''' is the most important thing in my life.}}
##* {{w|John Milton}} (1608-1674)
##*: He on his side / Leaning half-raised, with looks of cordial '''love''' / Hung over her enamoured.
## A feeling of intense [[attraction]] towards someone.
##: {{ux|en|I have never been in '''love''' as much as I have with you.}}
##* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=8
